node.text:
I’ve often been asked the question, “how do you feel about faux plants?”. The answer is simple, not everyone has the light or the care level to have living plants in their space. So I’d rather you bring in a faux plant than force a living plant into a space where it will suffer and eventually die.  Faux plants can elevate spots in your home where you never thought you’d be able to have greenery before. With all of the faux plants in the Hilton Carter for Target collection, my goal was to make them look as real as possible so that they could really bring that lush, calm feeling. Here are a few tips on where and how to style them! 🌿🙏🏾💚

node.text:
Placed on a pedestal so that she can be the living art that she is and also to make a smaller place have more of a presence in the room. The Ming Aralia is one of my favorites because of their delicate foliage and their Dr. Seuss like growth. Mine used to be fuller but has lost a few leaves in the move. Since then tho I have seen her bounce back nicely. 

Ok, so you want the planter but it’s a throwback that I got from @cb2. It doesn’t have a drainage hole, so I have a base tray inside of it and then place the Ming, in its nursery pot, on top of that. 🖤🌿

node.text:
LET THE LIGHT IN! I’ve never meet a wall that I didn’t want to make a window. Oh this was the pièce de résistance of our home. Ok, the kitchen is pretty dope too, but you know what I’m saying! 😉 This east and south facing room was one of the reason I told Fiona we needed this home. When we came to look at it, the windows in this room were all fixed(meaning they didn’t open). The door here was small and broken. But I looked past all of that because I knew I wanted to really blur the line of indoor/outdoor. Not only would this room nurse many of our plants but it would be the place where we would go to get away, entertain and open our home up to the outside. Not only by having large glass windows, but with accordion doors that opened up to the deck, making our sunroom even larger. Swipe to see the before and after and head to my stories to see the full breakdown. 🖤🙏🏾

“Just bought my dream house. You should stop by when you’re free so you can see it.” - Vory

node.text:
Yes, that’s an Australian tree fern sitting on our kitchen island. And yes, it can live there. Why? Well because it gets a lot of bright indirect light and watered often. I know you’re concerned that it’s gonna get cooked this close to the range, but I promise you it’s not close enough for that to happen. While it will live here for most of the year, I’ve been placing it outside, on the north side of our home, so that it can enjoy the intense humidity that Baltimore has to offer this time of year. This being the first time I’ve owned a home and had the ability to place plants outside, has changed me. It was bitter sweet to see how much they thrive during the spring and summer outdoors. It made me a little sad that I kept all of them indoors for such a long time, when many of them longed to be out in nature. For the ATF, the north side of our house protects it from getting kissed by the sun and dying. You know what, let me just share a few care tips, so you too can have a ATF to love. 

1. When it comes to light, the brighter the better. these babies can tolerate medium light but avoid direct sun at all cost. You don’t like sunburn and they don’t either. Love your plant like you love yourself! 📠

2. Water them often to make sure the top soil stays evenly moist. Their roots don’t like being completely dry, so keep them hydrated. Having them in my kitchen helps remind me to water it daily. If you’re struggling with when to water, get yourself a moisture meter. 

3. Select a soil that has great drainage but helps to hold moisture. Bark chips helps grow a healthier fern.  Remember, provide your roots with the love they need for your plants to thrive.

4. Speaking of thriving, they will show off when place in humid climates. That’s what going outside in spring and summer has changed the growth of mine immensely. Indoors I suggest misting them or placing a humidifier by them to help with humidity. It’ll make your plants foliage shine and your skin as well! I can’t vouch for what it’ll do to your hair. 😜

5. Put them in a ceramic glazed pot to retain moisture.

There you go! Stay safe and of course, stay wild!

node.text: A view from the original dining room to the NEW dining room! As many of you know, we swapped the kitchen and dining room to give ourselves and guests more room to gather in the kitchen. We saw the dining room as a place for formal dinners, puzzling(COVID shit) and where our kids can work on their homework. I wanted to make the space have a more open feel so we removed the wall between the two rooms and to soften the edges, we rounded the corners. Because this room used to be the original kitchen, the windows were small and up high to fit a countertop below them. Since we were changing out the windows anyway, we extended the windows lower to match the rest of the house. My vision was to keep this room simplistic. Not only with the decor but with the plants as well. I wanted to have a table that fit the room perfectly and had my heart set on a concrete table. But given the size of the room, there weren’t many options out there for the size and color of concrete I was looking for. So since we had a local shop, @lukeworks, make our concrete island, countertop and vanity, I figured why not see if he could make us a dining table as well. This way the color and texture of the concrete would match the other pieces and we could get the exact size we wanted. Tying the natural materials together from room to room, I went with a handmade walnut light fixture and walnut dining chairs. Check out my stories to hear more about it. 🖤

node.text: In designing our home renovations, my plan was to make sure the first floor seamlessly flowed from one room to the next. Not just by opening up the space but through its color story, the textures, the shapes and of course the vibes. When it came to the powder room, you can see this plan come to life in the red oak slats, the custom concrete vanity or in the tile flooring that touches on the colors throughout the entire home. When it came to the red oak slats, once I made the decision to have them in the sunroom, I knew I wanted to then bring them into the powder room as well. I wanted it to be an accent in the room, so limiting how much it covered was important. I’m a huge fan of symmetry but I love when something feels slightly off or organic. So instead of having the one wall completely covered in slats, I shifted it over slightly and had some spill onto the other wall as well, leaving it off centered. It was in that negative space that the vanity would go. Inspired by the counters at a local coffee shop @goodneighborshop , we hired the same company @lukeworks to do all of our concrete as well. So I sketched out the look I wanted and sent that over. In choosing the color of the concrete I wanted something on the lighter side to keep the room brighter and also asked for it to be poured in a certain way that would allow it to look more raw in appearance. The need for cubbies was clear so that we had a place for our hand towel and a small candle or 2. I wanted a wall mounted faucet, and because of the small space, going with only one cross handle felt right. Again, I got to play with being a bit off balanced. Now that the faucet would be wall mounted, a back splash was needed. So instead of just taking the concrete up to where the faucet was, I decided it would be a cleaner look to go up the entire wall, filling the rest of the space between the slats and flanking wall. Now we had one wall full of texture, weight and pop! We also now had many vertical lines and I wanted to break that up. So I found a mirror on Etsy that had a warped shape that was just slightly large enough to trail over on the slats, breaking up the hard lines. Head to my stories to see more🖤
